INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_dab3700','letter','1780-06-20','Fort Pitt','PA','US','Daniel','Brodhead','','George','Washington','','individual','','I have provisions, at the dependent posts, for four weeks to come ; and, by collecting all the cattle in the possession of the Commissaries, this garrison may be subsisted for the same term. But what I shall do for further supplies, I cannot devise','ltr_dab3700.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_dab3701','letter','1780-08-18','Fort Pitt','PA','US','Daniel','Brodhead','','George','Washington','','individual','','The Lieutenant of Monongalia county informs me, that ten men were killed on Friday last, above the forks of Cheat.','ltr_dab3701.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_dab3702','letter','1780-08-21','Fort Pitt','PA','US','Daniel','Brodhead','','George','Washington','','individual','','I am informed that the British at Detroit treat the French inhabitants with great severity, and that they wish for nothing more than the approach of a body of troops from this place.','ltr_dab3702.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_dab3703','letter','1780-09-05','Fort Pitt','PA','US','Daniel','Brodhead','','George','Washington','','individual','','Yesterday, the Indians killed two men, of the frontier inhabitants, on Robeson\'s Run, in this county (Yougluogania), and fired at two soldiers who were taking some stores in a canoe from hence to Fort Henry.','ltr_dab3703.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_dab3704','letter','1780-09-14','Fort Pitt','PA','US','Daniel','Brodhead','','George','Washington','','individual','','The French inhabitants at Detroit are much in our interest, and wish most heartily to see an American force approaching. I really believe that twelve hundred well-appointed men would carry that place without great difficulty','ltr_dab3704.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_dab3705','letter','1780-09-17','Fort Pitt','PA','US','Daniel','Brodhead','','George','Washington','','individual','','I have this moment received intelligence, that the enemy from Detroit intend paying a visit to this frontier.','ltr_dab3705.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_dab3706','letter','1780-12-07','Fort Pitt','PA','US','Daniel','Brodhead','','George','Washington','','individual','','I have, for a long time past, had two parties in the country, commanded by Field-Officers, to impress cattle, and yet the troops are frequently without meat for several days together.','ltr_dab3706.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_dab3707','letter','1781-02-25','Fort Pitt','PA','US','Daniel','Brodhead','','George','Washington','','individual','','The Indians have lately killed one man upon Ten Mile Creek, and the inhabitants are in great consternation. The frontier settlements will doubtless be deserted, as I have not troops to protect them.','ltr_dab3707.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_dab3708','letter','1781-03-27','Fort Pitt','PA','US','Daniel','Brodhead','','George','Washington','','individual','','Indeed, this place is infested with such a set of disaffected inhabitants, that I have been under the necessity of ordering some away, and others must soon follow, to prevent greater injury to the service.','ltr_dab3708.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_dab3709','letter','1781-08-29','Fort Pitt','PA','US','Daniel','Brodhead','','George','Washington','','individual','','The Maryland corps was stationed at a post on the frontier of Westmoreland county, and have in a body deserted and crossed the mountains. ','ltr_dab3709.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_dab3710','letter','1780-07-21','Fort Pitt','PA','US','Daniel','Brodhead','','George','Washington','','individual','','A few days ago I received intelligence, that a party, consisting of thirty odd Wyandot Indians, had crossed the Ohio River, five miles below Fort Mcintosh, and had hid thirteen small bark canoes upon our shore.','ltr_dab3710.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_dab3711','letter','1780-10-17','Fort Pitt','PA','US','Daniel','Brodhead','','George','Washington','','individual','','The Delaware Chiefs, with upwards of thirty warriors, are come to aid me upon an expedition ; but, as I have neither bread nor meat to give them, they will soon discover that it is not in my power to act offensively.','ltr_dab3711.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
